        tool_name: Read
        tool_response:
            file:
                content: |
                    # Orchestra Agents — Project Memory

                    ## Project State
                    - **Phase**: Phase 1 implementation in progress. Step 1 (proto contract) complete. Step 2 (Plugin SDK) next.
                    - **Reference**: `orch-ref/` contains the old monolith. 14 artifacts extracted to `docs/artifacts/`.
                    - **Architecture**: Microservices, event-driven, QUIC mesh, Protobuf messages, mTLS auth.

                    ## Key Decisions (see docs/artifacts/13-rebuild-decisions.md for full detail)
                    - Rewrite from scratch (don't copy orch-ref code)
                    - QUIC everywhere, WebTransport for browsers, Protobuf messages
                    - **Plugin host architecture** — minimal orchestrator (~500 lines Go) + N out-of-process plugins
                    - Star topology — orchestrator is the ONLY router, no direct plugin-to-plugin communication
                    - Protobuf contract (PluginHost service) — any language can be a plugin
                    - Always out-of-process — every plugin is a separate binary over QUIC
                    - Discovery via seed file (`~/.orchestra/plugins.yaml`) + mDNS for LAN
                    - **Feature-driven workflow** (not Scrum) — one feature doc per deliverable, no epic/story/task hierarchy
                    - Doc-first, TDD-driven — feature doc IS the spec, contains DOD + test cases + evidence
                    - **Cyclical delivery** — doc → implement → test → review → human → update → repeat until human says done
                    - Human review gate — agent delivers, human approves or requests edits (versioned in doc)
                    - "Done" = human approved. Not the agent, not the tests, not the gates. The human.
                    - **AgentOps** — track tokens, cost, API calls per feature per cycle (budget limits with alerts)
                    - **Time management** — complexity estimation, cycle count tracking, historical accuracy learning
                    - **Dependencies** — feature dependency graph, enforced ordering, blocker detection
                    - **Smart assignment** — domain→agent routing (backend→go-architect, engine→rust-engineer, etc.), per-agent WIP limits
                    - **Git workflow** — feature branches, cycle commits, merge on human approval, dependency-enforced branching
                    - **Notifications** — desktop/Slack/email alerts when human-review needed, budget exceeded, agent errors
                    - **Parallel conflict resolution** — file lock registry, soft/hard locks, conflict detection at merge, agent-resolved
                    - **Automated quality gates** — lint, type check, build, independent test runner, coverage, security scan at every gate
                    - Context-aware sizing — each feature must fit within the agent's context window
                    - Build order: Orchestrator → storage.markdown → transport.stdio → tools.features → Web → macOS
                    - **QUIC from day one** — no gRPC shortcuts, use quic-go + mTLS from the start
                    - Native UI per platform (no more Wails/webview)
                    - **No TOON** — replaced by Protobuf (structured metadata) + Markdown (content body)

                    ## Architecture (Plugin Host — see docs/artifacts/14-plugin-host-architecture.md)
                    - **Orchestrator**: Plugin loader, message router, event dispatcher, lifecycle manager
                    - **Plugin categories**: transport, storage, tools, engine, AI, integration, UI
                    - **Key plugins**: transport.stdio, storage.markdown, storage.sqlite, tools.features, engine.parse (Rust), ai.claude

                    ## Artifacts (docs/artifacts/)
                    - 00-10: Reference codebase analysis (14,491 total lines)
                    - 11: QUIC mesh architecture design (partially superseded by 14)
                    - 12: Monorepo directory structure
                    - 13: All rebuild decisions
                    - 14: Plugin host architecture (the definitive design)
                    - 15: Phase 1 implementation plan (QUIC + feature tools, step-by-step)
                    - 16: Feature-driven workflow (replaces Scrum — doc-first, TDD, cyclical until human approves)
                    - 17: AI reasoning & memory (inception, guided questions, per-project RAG)

                    ## Agents (22 total — .claude/agents/)
                    ### Core Protocol (3)
                    - `quic-protocol` — QUIC transport, mTLS, Protobuf framing, wire protocol
                    - `go-architect` — Go orchestrator, plugin SDK, Go plugins (quic-go)
                    - `rust-engineer` — Rust plugins (quinn, prost, Tree-sitter, Tantivy, rusqlite)
                    ### Native Plugin Languages (4)
                    - `swift-plugin` — Swift/macOS/iOS (Network.framework, SwiftUI, WidgetKit)
                    - `kotlin-plugin` — Kotlin/Android (Netty QUIC, Jetpack Compose)
                    - `csharp-plugin` — C#/Windows (System.Net.Quic, WinUI 3)
                    - `gtk-plugin` — C/Vala/Linux (GTK4, libadwaita, ngtcp2, Flatpak)
                    ### Database (6)
                    - `dba` — Cross-database coordination, sync protocol
                    - `postgres-dba` — PostgreSQL (pgvector, JSONB, tsvector, partitioning)
                    - `sqlite-engineer` — SQLite (rusqlite, go-sqlite3, WatermelonDB)
                    - `redis-engineer` — Redis (pub/sub, Streams, caching, rate limiting)
                    - `clickhouse-engineer` — ClickHouse (analytics, OLAP)
                    - `lancedb-engineer` — LanceDB (vector search, embeddings, AI memory)
                    ### Frontend & UI (3): frontend-dev, ui-ux-designer, mobile-dev
                    ### Platform (3): widget-engineer, platform-engineer, extension-architect
                    ### Other (3): ai-engineer, devops, scrum-master
                    ### QA (4): qa-go, qa-rust, qa-node, qa-playwright

                    ## Tech Stack Quick Reference
                    - Go: quic-go, grandcat/zeroconf (orchestrator + most plugins)
                    - Rust: quinn, prost, tree-sitter, tantivy, lancedb (engine plugins)
                    - Swift: Network.framework, SwiftProtobuf, SwiftUI, WidgetKit
                    - Kotlin: Netty QUIC / Cronet, protobuf-kotlin, Jetpack Compose
                    - C#: System.Net.Quic (.NET 8+), Google.Protobuf, WinUI 3
                    - C/GTK: GTK4, libadwaita, ngtcp2/quiche, protobuf-c, Meson
                    - Proto: buf for Go/TS/Swift/Kotlin/C#, prost-build for Rust, protobuf-c for C
                    - DB: PostgreSQL+pgvector, Redis+Streams, ClickHouse, SQLite, LanceDB
                    - Storage format: Protobuf metadata + Markdown body (no TOON/YAML frontmatter)
                filePath: /Users/fadymondy/.claude/projects/-Users-fadymondy-Sites-orchestra-agents/memory/MEMORY.md
                numLines: 82
                startLine: 1
                totalLines: 82
            type: text
